7","1133–1194":"1133–1194","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","about 1171":"about 1171","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1163":"1163","1150":"1150","1194":"1194","1182":"1182","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1133":"1133","1243":"1243","ABT 1190":"about 1190","about 1164":"about 1164","Fritwell, Oxfordshire, England":"Fritwell, Oxfordshire, England","Louth, Lincolnshire, England":"Louth, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pipard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Normand, Emile, Antoine, Cecile, Jean-Paul, Renald, Adrien, Aime, Andre, Aurel.","French:","nickname from Old French <i>pinard</i>, a small medieval coin, so named from <i>pin</i> ‘pine’ because it bore the device of a pine cone."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":51,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King J